\begin{abstract}

We introduce a structural framework called the First-Order Balance Spiral Computation and show that prime numbers can be characterized as elements outside this structure. Computational evidence up to $10^5$ suggests that odd primes coincide with the complement of balance-representable integers, up to finite exceptions. We further discuss implications for prime detection and the infinitude of primes.

\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

Prime numbers are traditionally defined by divisibility. In this paper, we propose a structural alternative: primes emerge as the complement of a balance-generating system.

\section{Definitions}

\textbf{Definition 1 (Strict First-Order Balance)}  

A natural number $N$ is strictly balanced if there exist distinct integers $a,b,c,d \ge 2$ such that:

\[

a+b+c+d = ab - cd = N

\]

\textbf{Definition 2 (Relaxed Balance)}  

We allow $0$ and $1$ each at most once.

\textbf{Definition 3 (Spiral Representability)}  

A number $N$ is spiral-representable if:

\[

ab - cd = N

\]

for distinct integers $a,b,c,d$, even if the sum condition fails.

\section{Structural Transformation}

From:

\[

a+b+c+d = ab - cd

\]

we derive:

\[

(a-1)(b-1) = (c+1)(d+1)

\]

Let:

\[

x = a-1,\quad y = b-1,\quad u = c+1,\quad v = d+1

\]

Then:

\[

xy = uv,\quad N = x+y+u+v

\]

\section{Main Theorem}

\textbf{Theorem 1}  

If $N > 1$ is an odd strictly balanced number, then $N$ is composite.

\textbf{Proof}  

From the transformation:

\[

N = (g+h)(r+s)

\]

which is a nontrivial factorization. ∎

\section{Computational Observation}

Up to $10^5$, we observe:

\[

\text{Odd non-balanced numbers} = \{1,9\} \cup \{\text{odd primes}\}

\]

This suggests:

\[

N \ge 3 \text{ odd},\quad

N \notin S \iff N \text{ is prime}

\]

\section{Prime Detection Principle}

\textbf{Conjecture}  

All odd composite numbers (except finite cases) are spiral-representable.

Then:

\[

N \text{ is prime} \iff N \notin S

\]

This yields a structural prime detection method.

\section{Infinitude of Primes}

If the complement of spiral-representable numbers is infinite, then primes are infinite.

Since natural numbers are infinite and spiral-representability does not cover all odd integers, primes must be infinite.

\section{Conclusion}

We propose that primes are not merely indivisible numbers, but elements outside a balance-generating structure.

